  "@id": "https://w3id.org/cdif/xas/reflectionplane",
  "@type": "skos:Concept",
  "prefLabel": {
    "@value": "Reflection plane",
    "@language": "en"
  },
  "definition": {
    "@value": "Miller indices (hkl) of the reflecting plane used by the monochromator crystal.",
    "@language": "en"
  },
  "note": {
    "@value": "Monochromator crystal property.  It’s not a physical surface, but a mathematical construct based on the periodic arrangement of atoms. A classic example of a reflection plane in crystallography is the (100) plane in a cubic crystal system.    Miller index: (100),     Interpretation: This plane intersects the x-axis at 1 unit, and is parallel to both the y- and z-axes (i.e., it never intersects them).     Physical meaning: It represents a set of atomic layers perpendicular to the x-axis, spaced at regular intervals.  Examples of Crystals used for X-ray monochromators: Si(111), Si(220), Si(311), Ge(111) https://www.iucr.org/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/60637/IUCr2011-XAFS-Tutorial_-Ascone.pdf",
    "@language": "en"
  },
  "inScheme": {
    "@id": "https://w3id.org/cdif/xas/CDIF4XAS_Reference_Concepts"
  },
  "seeAlso": "https://manual.nexusformat.org/classes/base_classes/NXcrystal.html#nxcrystal-reflection-field",
  "foaf:focus": {
    "@id": "http://purl.org/nexusformat/definitions/Field/NXcrystal/reflection"
  },
  "references": [
    "https://www.iucr.org/__data/assets/pdf_file/0004/60637/IUCr2011-XAFS-Tutorial_-Ascone.pdf",
    "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.14920226"
  ]
}
